Twelve 1 by 1 squares form a rectangle, as shown. What is the total area of the shaded region? [asy]
size(4cm);defaultpen(linewidth(0.75));

// Filled portions
fill((0, 4)--(0, 0)--(2, 0)--cycle, gray(0.75));
fill((0, 4)--(3, 4)--(3, 0)--cycle, gray(0.75));

// grid
int j;
for (j = 0; j < 4; ++j) {draw((j, 0)--(j, 4));}
for (j = 0; j < 5; ++j) {draw((0, j)--(3, j));}

//diagonals
draw((0, 4)--(3, 0)); draw((0, 4)--(2, 0));
[/asy] ||| The total area of the rectangle is $3 \times 4 = 12$. The shaded region comprises two triangles. The first triangle has a base of length 2 and height 4, giving an area of $\frac{1}{2}(2)(4)=4$. The second triangle has a base of length 1 and height 4, giving an area of $\frac{1}{2}(1)(4)=2$. Therefore, the unshaded area is $4 + 2 = 6$. Thus, the total area of the shaded regions is $12 - 6 = \boxed{6}$.

